Subject:Re: [Antenna-discussion] Another Crystal Radio Question
Kirk

Supposing it was an AM radio, which can be assumed, the wavelength
will be be 180-550 metres, so adjacent tables are a small fraction of
a wavelength apart.

But the main thing you are still lagging on is that antennas in AM
radios are mismatched by a factor of 60-80 dB.  That explains why
Oliver did not see an effect and why you won't either, if you took the
trouble to do the experiment.

Alan G3NOQ





On 28 October 2012 18:05, Kirk T McDonald <kirkmcd@princeton.edu> wrote:
> Oliver,
>
> We need to know the frequency of the station you tuned to, and the distance
> between the two radios, before we can comment further.
>
> Strictly, the two radios need to be within lambda/3 of one another before
> you could detect much of an effect.
>
> So, to do a good experiment, you need to move one radio around and plot the
> signal strength of the other as a function of the distance between them.
>
> ---------------
> A second caveat is that it is possible that the radios don't actually
> capture the maximum power that they could.   Because the radios have
> amplifiers, they work well enough even if they are not ideally "matched".
>
> Strictly, "matching" involves 2 separate conditions:
>
> A.   The antenna is "tuned" to be "resonant" via a tuning capacitor.
> This is surely done in your radios.
>
> B.   The load impedance of the "tuned" radio equals the radiation resistance
> of the "tuned" antenna.
>
> The radiation resistance varies with the frequency, but your radio probably
> has a fixed load resistance, chosen to be that of a frequency in the center
> of the tuning band.
>
> For a general frequency in that band, the radio won't actually be fully
> "matched", and the power extracted from the wave is less than maximum.   The
> amplifier makes up for this "loss".
>
> ----------
> So, to do an even better experiment, you should make your study at several
> different frequencies across the band.    The frequency at which you find
> the greatest "proximity effect" corresponds to the one for which the load
> resistance best matches the radiation resistance.
>
>
> --Kirk
>
