>
> I tuned in a local broadcast station, then switched on and off another
> radio in the same room which was tuned to the same station.  Then I
> left the second radio on, but changed the frequency to which it was
> tuned.  I was not able to hear any change nor see any change on the
> signal strength meter of the first radio.  Can you suggest a simple
> experiment/demonstration that I might do to demonstrate the principle
> described below?
>
> Many thanks,
> Ollie
> W2QXR
>
> Kirk wrote:
>
> "....  the capture area theorem tells us that a tuned receiver
> captures all the power in the incident wave over a circle of radius
> about 1 wavelength around the receiver.
>
> If two radios are located within one wavelength of one another, they
> will interfere destructively, and each will hear a smaller signal than
> if the other radio weren't present.
>
> AM wavelengths are long enough that this effect is not entirely negligible.
> If two cars pass one another while tuned to the same AM station, there
> will be bit of a fadeout on their radios.   This usually goes away as
> traffic changes, so you attribute these fadeouts to the poor quality
> of AM signals, etc.
>
>
> On 10/27/12, david vanhorn <kc6ete@gmail.com> wrote:
>>>
>>> Here's a site that claims that the difference between one bar and two on
>>> a
>>> cellphone is 6 dB.
>>> http://www.tested.com/news/**news/510-cell-phone-reception-**
>>>
>>> explained-what-the-bars-mean/<http://www.tested.com/news/news/510-cell-phone-reception-explained-what-the-bars-mean/>
>>>
>>> This is of the size of the possible effect of another cellphone in front
>>> of you in reducing your reception.
>>>
>>
>> It may be true that on some particular phone, a "bar" is 6dB.  I wouldn't
>> count on that being any sort of standard.
>>
>> The near field effects of putting one phone near another are complicated.
>> You would see a much more complicated picture if you looked at moving that
>> phone to various positions in a cubical grid around the reference phone,
>> against a signal from a reference antenna out many meters.  Another
>> interesting experiment would be to create a low loss resonant circuit with
>> simply a loop and tuning capacitor, load that, and repeat the gridding.
>> The second phone, in the near field, is also acting as part of the antenna
>> system of the reference phone.
>>
>> I don't think your lunar thought experiment scales very well, there are
>> many orders of magnitude difference in the ratio of wavelength vs
>> obstructor.
